A black box in your car?
While planners in the U.S. highway system find it difficult to find the money to repair decaying highway infrastructure, many see a solution in the form of a small black box that binds over your car's dashboard.
The aircraft, which records all miles travelled by a motorist and transmits the information to government officials, is at the centre of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government planning offices to redesign the outdated financing system for major American roads.
The generally uninteresting sector of the planning of the major axes suddenly provoked a lively debate and turbulent alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to press for the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you travel, and eventually the road you travel on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses concern about the protection of privacy.
And while the members of Congress cannot agree whether to continue, several states have not waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they can move on to a system that allows drivers to pay according to the number of miles travelled.
Thousands of motorists have already boarded these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS surveillance system, for an experimental ride.
This is truly indispensable for our nation.
"It's not like we have the choice," said Hasan Ikhrata, Managing Director of the Southern California Association of Governments, who predicts that the state will start recording the miles travelled by every Californian motorist by 2025.
There will be some change in the way we pay these taxes.
The technology is there to do it.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country's Highway Trust Fund, financed with the taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans don't buy as much gas as they used to.
Cars can travel more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in the last 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by 1 cent, while gasoline prices are high.
"The gas tax is simply not sustainable," said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His State had recently installed tracers on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
"It turns out to be the most logical alternative in the long term," he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces city liberals, since taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the objectives set out in the ambitious state laws on global warming.
But Bill Shuster (R-Pa.), Speaker of the House of Representatives' Transport Committee, said he also considered it to be the most viable alternative in the long term.
The reason foundation's supporters of the free market also appreciate the idea of making drivers pay for the mile.
"It's not just a tax swinging into a big black hole," said Adrian Moore, Vice President of Politics at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. secretaries of transportation who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to move towards payment by mile.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project last year that would have involved approximately 10,000 cars.
But the Speaker of the House killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to get to their work or to the city.
However, several States and major cities are making progress on their part.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to lead the country's most important experience.
These motorists will soon pay the state kilometric fees instead of fuel taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The city of New York is considering one.
Illinois is testing a limited number of trucks.
And coalition I-95, which includes 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the east coast of the United States (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is exploring how it could implement change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer motorists recently equipped their cars with a device, drivers were concerned that the government could follow their every move.
"Concerns about Big Brother and this kind of thing are a big problem," said Alauddin Khan, who leads the strategic performance management in Nevada's Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
From the beginning of the test, the Nevada ACLU warned on its site: "It would be relatively easy to transform these devices into full localization devices."
There is no need to build a huge and bulky technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people's day-to-day whereabouts.
Nevada is one of the few states that are now struggling to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car runs, but without knowing the exact location and time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
The search for this technology has led some state agencies to use a small California startup called True Mileage.
Initially, the company did not aim to assist motorists who pay taxes to states.
It sought to break into the emerging auto insurance market, in which drivers would pay according to their mileage.
But the devices it tests have liked the planners of the major axes because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, downloaded periodically by modem.
"People will be more inclined to do this if you don't record their speed and locate them," said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Major errors have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much cheaper ways and much less intrusive methods of proceeding.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering motorists different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have a device at all, preferring instead to pay a flat rate based on the average number of miles travelled by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transport officials are seeking to develop a tax system that would also be equipped to pay parking costs, provide "driving payment" insurance, and create a real-time speed data set from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic congestion.
"Motorists would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits the system offers them," said an urban development document.
However, some transport planners are wondering whether the whole debate on payment per mile is not simply a huge diversion.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission in the San Francisco Bay area, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by increasing taxes on gasoline.
An additional single or annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume much petrol, so that everyone pays their fair share.
"There is no need for radical surgery when you simply need aspirin," said Randy Rentschler, Director of Legislation and Public Affairs at the Commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists will worry about protecting their privacy and a lot of other things.
