On the other hand, the boss of the powerful NSA, General Keith Alexander, denied him that his intelligence agency had captured tens of millions of communications from European citizens.
He even sent the bullet back to the European intelligence services who allegedly seized the communications, before supplying them to the NSA.
This would involve "military operations" in countries where these NATO allies cooperate with the United States and it would not be Europe at all, said General Alexander.
