But since Edward Snowden, the whistle-blowing consultant, has begun to reveal his inexhaustible wealth of information about the secrets of US surveillance, European governments and business leaders no longer know whether to believe the director on his word.
Reports that the U.S. National Security Agency spied on the Brazilian petroleum company Petrobras and had access to data held by U.S. cloud storage service providers, including Google and Yahoo, have more than ever aroused corporate paranoia about state surveillance.
The revelation that the telephone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel had been hacked, perhaps even for a decade, was the drop of water that overflowed the vase.
If the most powerful person in Europe can be targeted, then business leaders are surely also potential targets.
