Why should an independent Scotland follow Europe's instructions, in fact?
Why trade the yoke of London for the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe is definitely at a standstill.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties that oppose the EU or advocate the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Alternative Eurosceptic Party for Germany, founded only this year and arrived from nowhere, gathered almost five million votes in the federal elections in September and removed the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been a national opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the carcano on national economies through accession to the single currency, has led many to believe that the Europe Project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments with excessive budget deficits - this was only true for Greece.
Instead, the European system has put favourable exchange rates on its members for German exporters - which German politicians want to maintain.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe find themselves with a problem of intrinsic productivity vis-à-vis Germany.
The only remedy is to cut wages and public expenditure - encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is a deeper malaise linked to productivity in Europe.
Following the "green" energy policies imposed by Brussels - which are a reason for subsidizing French and German energy companies at consumer's expense - European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than the United States.
This is a debilitating cost disadvantage, as we have seen in Grangemouth.
Not all wage freezes in the world will prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt is raging, particularly in France, one of the EU's leading leaders.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a means of controlling Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport of its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the French economy struggling.
As a result, the extreme right-wing party of Marine Le Pen, the National Anti-European Front, has just won a crucial by-election, returning the Socialists to power in third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the votes - a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split of the right will automatically favour the left.
What is Marine Le Pen doing with its new popularity among the French white working class?
It wants to use next year's European elections to create a single anti-European currency block in the European Parliament.
If anti-European parties were to be good at these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
That is what I think: very soon, the anti-European and anti-single currency sentiment in Europe will unify and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something that will be more like a "Europe of Nations (sovereign)" free privileged by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies could keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will regain their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project, and I hope that it will look soft in the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left behind in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland?
We can decide to be a region of small England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending Berlin and Brussels for a walk.
