Early puberty: Aging earlier
Studies show that African American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty age earlier than white girls.
Physical changes don't mean puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts think the obesity epidemic could be a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is not as pronounced among boys
The former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Does a mother have to worry if her daughter's pubic breasts and hair start to grow at 7 or 8 years of age?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics held this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, a child endocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young American women and represent a new standard.
"I spend a lot of time reassuring parents - in general, this does not indicate a rapid evolution towards full puberty," Kaplowitz said.
The obvious signs of development, such as breast budding, hair under the arms and in the pubic zone and body odours, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight increase in the age of the first rules over the last four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half years, compared to 12 years three quarters in 1970.
"Once the chest has begun to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first rules appear," said Kaplowitz, also the author of "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem."
Time is the most accurate test for how puberty will evolve.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered "early" when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, development slows or stops - it's something a pediatrician can follow closely.
A faster progression may justify testing by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumours or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of the first rules and prevent other consequences: premature aging of bones that can slow growth and small size in adulthood.
Drug and hormonal treatment recommendations are based on child age, developmental rate, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psycho-social aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is careful with medication but recognizes that "controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioural problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others."
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don't want their very young girls to have their rules.
"They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they will deal with hygiene issues," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period when she was 10.
Even if there were signs and we talked about the rules, she wasn't emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories brought to the public's attention about the causes of early puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz states that the most credible hypothesis is that of the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study of girls between the ages of 6 and 9 years, which linked the percentage of fat to the onset of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty age earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, mechanisms of early puberty seem to be influenced by everything, from economic conditions to climate, to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have hair on their faces and in the younger pubic zone, the trend towards genuine early puberty is not as pronounced as among girls.
Other physicians attending the PAA conference emphasized the complexity of the topic.
Acne and pubic hair are common, even in infants and toddlers.
"We need to be careful about how we identify the true appearance of puberty," said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a child endocrinologist working at the Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This may mean having a conversation earlier than expected," Kaplowitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will react well in general.
Girls with early puberty need to be reassured that even when it happens sooner than expected, the process is part of life.
