How biometrics will invade our lives
Are you done typing passwords to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy director general of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric."
Only biometrics will make it possible to ascertain the identity of a person carrying out transactions in a world as transverse and transnational as the Internet.
The privacy organizations confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned about it.
In 2011 alone and in France, the National Commission on Informatics and Freedoms authorised 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the shape of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
"Everyone can soon be identified, anywhere and anytime," says Justin Brookman, Consumer Privacy Officer at the Center for Democracy and Technology (CDT) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will enable new services to be rendered to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, the outline of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people working on concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible," says Philippe Robin, Technical Director of Identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand implies a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
This is both a security - it cannot be captured without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been carried out over the past 20 years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the coloured part of the eye).
With increased sensor accuracy and computer computing capacity required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the last five years, calculates Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture's R & D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," says Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
A unique and infalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," says Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective Studies at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and expensive.
NEC offers criminal investigation services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in an hour.
Biometrics uses are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is the person they claim to be).
So far, the identification concerned the issue of identity documents: biometric elements (fingerprints, photo, iris) must be compared with the information that the state has on all citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person does not attempt to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance to a hotel or shop.
"We get images from surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities who are freely circulating on the Internet," explains Dany Nassif, NEC France's business development manager for biometric identification solutions.
Other use: take a photo of a quidam in line in a store, track its progress through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical access (opening a computer).
In addition, more recently, there has been monitoring of attendance.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend who points for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, d'Accenture.
But more and more authentication will also concern transactions, especially those involving devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric reader: this act replaces the striking of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by Natural Security in partnership with banks and retail brands: when paying in-store with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader who scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is successful, biometric readers could soon arrive at the French merchants' premises.
Ways to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer stays in cash for 30 seconds less, it's worth it," explains the manager of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you tailor-made options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which blocks itself if one tries to move it," lists Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, in the absence of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
The privacy community continues to be concerned.
"The advances in facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance," says Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner of Canada.
