Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog's tail are related to his mood.
Previous studies had shown that happy dogs moved their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs moved more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "Everyone knows that in man, the left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was happening with other species.
He added that, as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies with other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behaviour.
It will certainly not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We have presented to dogs films containing other dogs - either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factor - and we have been able to manipulate the tail movement and present it as going left or right."
When the animals saw a dog without expression stirring the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog stirring the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail moving mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog stirring the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said that he did not believe that dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Instead, he thinks that dogs know from experience what movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet other dogs repeatedly and you notice that most of the time the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side causes a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience."
Researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
The canine behaviour expert John Bradshaw, visiting professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said, "Dogs went more easily to a robot dog when his tail moved to the left than to the right, instead of becoming anxious - the opposite of what appeared in the Italian study."
He indicated that the differences could arise from the fact that the dogs who participated in the different studies did not fully consider the animals in the movies or robotic dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs might be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements, found in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified - and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviours can be recorded, it will certainly not be long before we understand why their tails sometimes move on one side and sometimes on the other.
