A team of biologists led by the New York Wildlife Conservation Society has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, Scientific Officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Habitats (OCEAMM), returns for L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new humpback dolphin surprise you?
That is good news, but I am not particularly surprised.
While species have in the past been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge of species classification sciences.
It is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to call into question the classification or membership of a species in a genus, family or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals on the basis of morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being challenged because of advances in genetics.
Similarly, two closely related morphologically distinct species were distinguished through genetics.
This is the case with the newly identified species.
A decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific humpback dolphins and Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have identified four species.
Why is this a major discovery as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and hence its genetic variability.
If this population had long been known to researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only there.
Therefore, if there is a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture in the region, we may have to deal with the extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a species more widespread on Earth.
This loss of genetic resources would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or extirpated based on the number of individuals on Earth, that is, the stock, and the ability to recover from neighbouring stocks.
For the species Sousa chinensis, from which the population of the new discovered species originated, its stock has automatically become smaller, thus making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene mixing limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
The marine environment is the least well known.
We'd rather send robots to Mars, than find out what lives in the Mariana pit, just 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
We spend more money in the search for life on other planets than in marine research, and it is high time that this change.
