Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopedias de Satie.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from ink black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, advances, of profile, fine as a line and clothed in black, a body.
On the screen, Henri Michaux's ink is projected.
The body, a simple trait, takes its shape.
And this form will be the shape of the whole piece: an enfilade of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, only with their hands and face uncovered, wait on either side of the playing area, rush when the next drawing appears, embody it, run out.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is done in solos relay, in unison group (a mass that makes solo), in large group of twelve solos where each one executes his sign.
We think of "Glory of the morning," where, as a solo, Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, posed online in the foreground.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is strong, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the rhythm always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance mat, to deliver, micro in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of the poem of Michaux, monocord and monotonous in the scream, and continue dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to go back.
This long, energetic sound discharge, if possible, ends up deafening and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes - the creation of images has always been a strength at Chouinard - like those hair that crumbles or those black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet Michaux's work, has established herself, with her tics.
As a result, the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
The inks of Michaux, like forms of Gestalt, open up a broader and giboyous imagination than dance, which is more porous.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers chopped by strobe light and white signs in a suddenly black theatre, touches magic.
The audience liked it, the reception was warm.
The Gymnopedias, after intermission, are richer.
The stage is partly covered in grey, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in a abandoned house.
At the piano, dancers turn around to play the scores.
Their touching music clumsiness gives a real fragility.
On stage, couples pass, in love duos, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving sets, choirs, writing is less binary.
Some buffoons appear, also familiar with Chouinard, with a red nose, in very polarized male-female loving parades.
The lovers are carnassiers, runners or players.
The gestural, the laughter, and the little cries are deeply transposing the archaic, the grace and the ridicule of the bodies into coitus, of the beings who merge.
But the play takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown comes back on stage when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes allowed: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes superimpose themselves, the dancers cabotinate, descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short-circuit, play applause codes, stretch the sauce in a skilfully calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness are sweeping, and it is Chouinard's art to contaminate the public.
