Walking in mud, jungle and crossing rivers to offer free medical assistance
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free health care in villages in Cameroon
Dr. Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend seeing hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in this West African country, barely 1 per 5,000 inhabitants.
Vote here or via your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 CNN Heroes of the Year 2013.
You can vote for him, or one of the other 10 heroes, to elect him "CNN Hero of the Year."
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternate periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and go to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only one broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma whose sequelae he was going to carry the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to busy clinics and hospitals to get any treatment he could get.
"It's not easy," says Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5: 00, run to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since the death of Dr. Bwelle's father in 2002.
In Cameroon, there are only 1 doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
By way of comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians would not be able to pay for the consultation.
Two out of every five people in the country live below the poverty line, and almost three quarters of the country & apos; s health expenditure is in the private sector.
"The only problem they have is poverty," said Dr. Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they can't enjoy life.
After seeing his father and as many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers have performed more than 700 surgeries free of charge over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the central hospital in Yaoundé.
And it has established a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which visits rural areas during weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about 30 people, they pile up in vans after they have fixed the medical equipment on the roof and cross difficult terrain to reach the villages that need the most help.
Luck doesn't always follow them.
They have repeatedly had to push vehicles to cross rivers or muddy runways.
But when they arrive, they are received as heroes: the community organizes a party, sings and dances and offers them the best accommodation available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to celebrate, and Dr. Bwelle - with his big smile and overflowing energy - is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
"We receive 500 people each time," said Mr. Bwelle.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this travelling hospital, various health care services are provided.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, a pair of glasses collected or a free birth certificate - a document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford it.
In the evening, the team practices simple surgical procedures under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school, town hall or house; after the intervention, the patient rises and goes to the alarm room to leave his or her place to the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the first hours of Sunday morning.
It's a hectic rhythm, but the village musicians usually help the team stay motivated.
"They're hitting drums all night to keep us awake so we can keep working," said Mr. Bwelle.
On Sundays, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work it has done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, has performed 700 surgeries free of charge over the past year, and knows that their presence can make all the difference for those they help.
One man explained that the free operation he had undergone to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
"This will change my future and that of my family," the man said.
In addition to living this traveling hospital and working as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, which finances 60% of his association; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't know when he's sleeping," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Dr. Bwelle's group.
He is still in hospital or trying to find money for his association so that he can run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, this is a field learning opportunity they don't have at home.
"We were able to participate in operations to help clean up the blood or pass the instruments on to Dr. Bwelle," said Ms. O'Malley.
This is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you're a medical student in second year.
Volunteer students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, transportation and teaching are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
"He's a hero, there's no doubt," said Katie O'Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not nearly extinguished.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a problem.
Helping others live happily by keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," added Mr. Bwelle.
And I'm thinking about my dad.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons why I do this.
