John Kerry admitted, made unprecedented, that American espionage "went too far inappropriately"
John Kerry indicated a softening of the defensive attitude of the United States towards its surveillance programs by acknowledging, without precedent, that on several occasions espionage "went too far in an inappropriate way."
The Secretary of State also admitted that, like Barack Obama, he had ruled on "autopilot" when a series of inflammatory revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA's espionage activities came into being.
The leaks put the US government at the centre of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at an intergovernmental conference in London via video link, Mr Kerry said: "It is undeniable that the President, myself and other members of the government learned of some things in automatic pilot mode because we had the possibility, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, and then of course on 11 September."
He then became the first high-ranking member of the United States government to admit that American espionage had crossed the line, but insisted that everyone's rights had not been violated.
He said, "In some cases, it went too far inappropriately."
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make it clear to people that he is now carrying out a thorough review of these practices so that no one feels wrong.
I assure you that innocent people will not be abused in this process.
Mr. Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for the good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added: "We live in a new world where people are ready to blow themselves up."
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, blow them up and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We did prevent planes from falling, buildings from exploding, and people from being murdered because we were able to get to know the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, US legislators will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged US espionage case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the US, said the President of the Senate Sub-Committee on European Affairs on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said that he had spoken before the Members of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about the threats they had made regarding the possible withdrawal of anti-terrorist organizations because of the frustration with the supervision of the National Security Agency.
"It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans stay with us in our mutual commitment to the fight against terrorism," said Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and Chairman of the Sub-Committee on European Affairs of the United States Senate, during an interview from Washington.
And I will go to Europe to make them understand that we must continue to work together to fight terrorism, despite the anger caused by the NSA programmes.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has damaged relations with some of the US allies, but the agency's director said this week that it was inaccurate and that it was a misunderstanding because it concerned metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the US.
Other revelations referred to documents disclosed by Snowden that the NSA had intercepted data and communications from the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and those of 34 other Heads of State.
The Director of Intelligence, James Clapper, justified the espionage of the allies by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this tumultuous atmosphere, Murphy indicated that his office was organizing a trip to Congress, which should take place this year, and that he hoped that the delegation would include members of both parties and chambers.
The names of other participating legislators should be announced in the coming days.
He indicated that the route remained to be defined.
Murphy stated that the purpose of this trip was to improve relations, but also to show "loving firmness."
He explained that European heads of state must be honest with their citizens about the type of espionage programmes they have been implementing themselves for years.
"We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they must also understand that we are not the only ones in the world who spy," Murphy said.
Meanwhile, Mr. Kerry has planned to travel this weekend to the Middle East and Poland to manage the resentment generated by American strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as by the surveillance activities of the United States.
