Australian woman appeals prison sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney resident, sentenced to 15 days in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been assaulted by a taxi driver, appealed the judgement and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was first found guilty by a Phuket Provincial Court on June 15 of false statements after telling the Thai police that a local taxi driver, accompanied by two other men who mastered her, had assaulted her early on Sunday, June 10.
However, video surveillance footage later revealed that she had safely returned to her hotel after separating from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interviewed Bamford for two days before she confessed to having invented the whole story.
She was detained in a cell at the local police station prior to the court hearing.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days imprisonment in a low-security detention facility on the outskirts of Phuket rather than in a women's prison.
This is the daughter of former Australian rugby league player Peter Tunks, who appealed to the Canberra Ministry of Foreign Affairs to help his daughter.
Tunks told Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was "extremely concerned" with her daughter's well-being and wanted her to return to Australia.
"We've obviously had a very distressing time, but we hope to take her home safely as soon as possible," Tunks said.
Bamford appealed the judgement and was released after a bail of 50,000 baht.
In Australia, the press said that in the meantime, she was on vacation in the Krabi region of southern Thailand.
Thai judicial sources indicated that Bamford was represented by a local Phuket lawyer, but warned that the appeal could lead to an increased sentence of up to two years' imprisonment and imprisonment in an adult prison.
However, following the recent murder in Phuket of Michelle Smith, an Australian travel agent, Thailand could also seek to restore its deteriorated image to tourists, which could lead to acquittal.
